===Etymology===
From New Latin '''[[saturatus]]''', perfect passive participle of '''[[saturare]]''', from '''[[saturus]]''', future passive participle, from '''[[satis]]''', ''enough''.

==English==

===Verb===

'''saturate''', '''[[saturates]]''', '''[[saturating]]''', '''[[saturated]]'''

#Cause to become completely [[penetrate]]d, [[impregnate]]d, or [[soak]]ed; fill fully; sate.
#Satisfy the affinity of; cause to become inert by chemical combination with all that it can hold; as, saturate phosphorus with chlorine.

====Translations====
